91: I thought hard about where was my field going, where were the opportunities, and what were the important things to do. Let me go there so there is a chance I can do important things.

95: The great scientists, when an opportunity opens up, get after it and they pursue it. They drop all other things. They get rid of other things and they get after an idea because they had already thought the thing through.

101 op: He seems to be deeply unsatisfied with the status quo and is constantly looking for way to change it and improve it. First, when he jointed the Bell Labs, he saw that we was different from, or maybe than, Shannon et. al. and he started asking the questions ``why'' and ``how to change that''. Secondly, he used to change tables we would eat his lunch at to keep learning and keep discovering what important problems in other fields were. He even challenged his lunch-mates on why they don't work on important problems, as if it made him uneasy (like me). Thirdly, even the fact that he was doing super successful work was not satisfying for him, because he was ``only'' solving single problem instances. He wanted his work to be more general and further-reaching, so he decided to change his approach and take every single problem he faced to recast it into an instance of a more general problem and then he proceeded to adapt instance-based solutions to something that fits the more general framework, thereby created a very general solution to the whole class of problems. Now, this approach takes a lot of additional work despite what he says about it, but the work itself has the potential of being applicable in many other cases, useful for others and therefore memorable.
With tracking, I've solved a single instance of the problem. I haven't describe the general algorithm or the underlying principles of how or why it works, but it would be much useful and much general if I had. I think it would be interesting to revisit the problem and find out. It's not about tracking, it's about how and why exactly attention and attention-bbox decomposition is useful from the learning and function-approximation perspectives.

105: The business of abstraction frequently makes things simple.

