Side-note: Why Reading >> Listening/Watching
I've always been a fan of reading and I thought it's cognitively superior to both listening and watching, that it is more engaging and, oddly enough, more interactive. I never quite thought about or could explain why I think that. Surely listening to an audiobook must have exactly the same merits as reading a book, no? Well, I've always thought listening to an audiobook is just lazy. Now, here's the reason I think I've been using all this time but couldn't quite verbalise:

Listening is passive in the sense that you cannot stop and think about it. That's why it's easy to watch even though-provoking movies and block them out, doze off. While you can think about what's going on, you have very limited time to do so because new content is streaming in. Even if you doze off for a second, you may not notice or easily ignore it when your attention is captured by a new development.

You can do that while reading a book, too, but at least for me, it has been much more-easily noticeable and harder to cope with. I hate not understanding a paragraph and I always try to re-read enough it times to understand it before going further. I also pause often and reflect on what I've just read, exactly how I'm doing now, reading this talk. This sparks a conversation with the author, allows me to think about causes and consequences, permits me to understand deeply. This makes reading much more active and also interactive then simply listening or watching.

181: How the WW II shaped later discoveries:
Because many of us were earlier forced to learn other things - we were forced to learn the things we didn't want to learn, we were forced to have an open door - and then we could exploit those things we learned.

189: Brainstorming:
What you want to do is get that critical mass in action; ``Yes, that reminds me of so and so,'' or, ``Have you thought about that or this?'' When you talk to other people, you want to get rid of those sound absorbers who are nice people but merely say, ``Oh yes,'' and to find those who will stimulate you right back.

199: If you read all the time what other people have done you will think the way they thought. If you want to think new thoughts that are different, then do what a lot of creative people do - get the problem reasonably clear and then refuse to look at any answers until you've thought the problem through carefully how you would do it, how you could slightly change the problem to be the correct one.

207: Public talks are necessary; private talks are necessary; written papers are necessary. But I am inclined to believe that, in the long-haul, books which leave out what's not essential are more important than books which tell you everything because you don't want to know everything. I don't want to know that much about penguins is the usual reply. You just want to know the essence.


215: I wouldn't even read papers to try to force myself to have a chance to do something else. I managed myself, which is what I'm preaching in this whole talk. Knowing many of my own faults, I manage myself. I have a lot of faults, so I've got a lot of problems, i.e. a lot of possibilities of management.

219: When your vision of what you want to do is what you can do single-handedly, then you should pursue it. The day your vision, what you think needs to be done, is bigger than what you can do single-handedly, then you have to move toward management.
